<h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-white mb-2 leading-tight">Scrabble Clock Management</h1>
<p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8 not-prose">Dictionary · Word of the Day</p>

<p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mb-6">Published June 15, 2026 · 6 min read</p>

<p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-8">In tournament Scrabble, time is a finite resource — 25 minutes per player, ticking away on a chess clock. How you allocate those minutes across 12-15 turns determines whether you finish with time to spare or haemorrhage points to overtime penalties. Here's how the best players manage the clock.</p>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Tournament Time Rules</h2>

<div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
  <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">25 min</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Standard time per player</p></div>
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">-10 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Per minute overtime</p></div>
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">~1.5 min</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Average per turn</p></div>
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">12–15</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Turns per game</p></div>
  </div>
</div>

<p>Most tournaments use chess clocks where each player has an independent 25-minute countdown. After playing a word and recording your score, you hit the clock to start your opponent's timer. Going overtime costs 10 points per minute — a devastating penalty that can turn a win into a loss.</p>

<div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
  <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Reality Check</p>
  <p class="text-base text-gray-200">The average tournament game lasts <span class="text-white font-medium">12-15 turns per player</span>. With 25 minutes, that's roughly 1.5-2 minutes per turn on average. But not all turns are equal — some require 10 seconds, others 4 minutes. The art is distributing time unevenly to match board complexity.</p>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Time Allocation Strategy</h2>

<div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Opening (turns 1-3):</span> Spend 30-60 seconds per turn. The board is small, options are limited, and the best opening plays are well-studied. Don't overthink — play your strongest word and move on.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Midgame (turns 4-10):</span> Budget 1.5-2.5 minutes for complex positions. This is where the board has multiple open lanes, bingo possibilities, and defensive considerations. Invest time here — it pays the highest returns.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Endgame (turns 11-15):</span> Reserve 3-5 minutes for the final turns. Endgame requires tile tracking, spread calculation, and precise placement. Running low on time here is catastrophic — you can't afford mistakes when every point matters.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Speed Techniques</h2>

<div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
  <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 The 5-Second Scan</p>
  <p class="text-base text-gray-200">When it's your turn, spend the <span class="text-white font-medium">first 5 seconds scanning for obvious plays</span> — a hook, an extension, or a high-value letter on a premium square. If you spot one scoring 30+, verify it quickly and play. Only dig deeper if nothing obvious presents itself.</p>
</div>

<div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
    <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Pre-plan on opponent's time</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">While they think, scan the board for your next move. When it's your turn, verify their play didn't block you, then execute.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
    <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Memorise 2-letter words</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Knowing all 127 valid two-letter words by heart saves verification time. You'll hook words faster without mental dictionary checks.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/10">
    <p class="text-blue-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Set time checkpoints</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Glance at your clock after turns 5 and 10. If you've used more than 60% at turn 10, speed up immediately.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/10">
    <p class="text-blue-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Accept "good enough"</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">A 28-point play found in 30 seconds beats a 33-point play that took 3 minutes. The 5-point difference rarely justifies 2.5 minutes of clock.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
